== Practice Problems == 1. John collected 14 cans. Tim brought in 10 cans. Suzy got 3 cans from her house and 15 more from her father's work. {{hidden|contentstyle = text-align: center; |How many cans of food did Suzy collect?|18}} {{hidden|contentstyle = text-align: center; |How many cans of food were collected by all three children?|42}}
2. Billy broke a stick into 3 pieces. The first piece of the stick is 53 cm long. The second piece of the stick is 29 cm long. *{{hidden|contentstyle = text-align: center; |If the stick was 120 cm long before Billy broke it how long is the third piece?|38 cm}}
<noinclude>{{Simple Page Navigation|BookName=[[Basic Algebra]]|CurrentPage=The Ideas of Algebra|PrevPage=[[Basic Algebra/Introduction to Basic Algebra Ideas/The Ideas of Algebra|The Ideas of Algebra]]|NextPage=[[Basic Algebra/Introduction to Basic Algebra Ideas/Simple Operations|Simple Operations]]}}</noinclude> {{BookCat}}

A set of cards is called a '''pack'''. A normal pack has 52 cards in it. These are split into four types, known as '''suits''', called '''hearts''', '''clubs''', '''diamonds''' and '''spades'''. There are numbers on the cards, and there is one card of each number in each suit. Some of the cards have a letter rather than a number on them: ones have the letter '''A''' on them, and are known as '''aces''', elevens, twelves and thirteens are known as '''Jacks''', '''Queens''' and '''Kings''', and have the letters J, Q, and K on them. Some games use special cards called '''jokers'''. If jokers are used, there are usually 54 cards in the pack.

==The pack==
The following cards are in a pack:

